## SECTION 2: Paulo Blikstein's semiotic critique — "Educational Soylent" and the politics of edtech

Paulo Blikstein (Teachers College, Columbia; formerly Stanford) has produced the most theoretically sophisticated critique of automated education. His work draws on semiotics, critical pedagogy, and constructionism to expose the ideological architecture beneath edtech discourse.

### The convenient antagonist and the political function of edtech discourse

In **"Do Educational Technologies Have Politics?"** (co-authored with Izidoro Blikstein, in M. Ito et al., eds., *Algorithmic Rights and Protections for Children*, MIT Press, 2022/2023; DOI: 10.1162/ba67f642.646d0673), Blikstein applies three Bakhtinian lenses — intertextuality, polyphony, dialogism — to a century of edtech rhetoric. The central finding: edtech entrepreneurs construct a "convenient antagonist" — a caricatured version of the lecture — to justify intervention. As Blikstein writes: **"The creation of this convenient antagonist was much easier than battling the entire educational system with its obsession for tests, outdated and overcrowded curriculum, or oppressive, racist incentive systems. Fighting such a system would entail critiques of power, privilege, control, and inequality — it is much more convenient to limit the problem to an uncomplicated and less controversial target: lecturing."**

This move enables a critical sleight of hand: edtech entrepreneurs "selectively appropriate the critique of traditional schooling by progressive educators, minus the overarching analysis of the historical, economic, and political reasons that generated the 'lecture.' The task at hand thus became to replace it while keeping the rest of the superstructure intact. **No venture capitalist wants to finance the disruption of the social order** or complicated discussions about educational and social justice."

### "Educational Soylent" and the stratification warning

Blikstein's most devastating analogy compares automated education to the meal-replacement drink Soylent: "To be successful, Soylent had to make customers believe that cooking and eating were a waste of time and that food was just about getting the essential nutrients into the body efficiently." Similarly, adaptive platforms must convince users that learning is "just about getting the essential nutrients" — content delivered in personalized sequences. "Public education could adapt to what low-cost automated instruction and AI can do, feeding their students glorified educational Soylent, while affluent schools will continue to offer rich, complex, hard-to-automate learning experiences for their students."

This leads to his sharpest prediction: **"Automated and AI-based educational systems — in their current inception — could become the ultimate tool for educational stratification and inequity."** Poorer districts, facing budget pressures, will adopt cheap automation; wealthier schools will continue offering project-based, relational instruction.

### The tycoons' discourses of urgency and heroism

In **"'I'm Not Trying to Sell Anything': Technology Tycoons' Discourses of Urgency and Heroism"** (Campos & Blikstein, *Proceedings of ICLS 2023*, International Society of the Learning Sciences), a critical discourse analysis of Steve Jobs, Bill Gates, and Salman Khan identifies four narrative genres: discourses of antagonism (creating the enemy), urgency (demanding immediate action), corporate heroism ("technology leaders establish themselves as Great Men"), and disruption (positioning specific products as the solution). The Antagonism-Urgency pair "serves to justify the urge towards products and ideas **without the need to describe current educational systems in more precise and accurate ways, nor to provide robust evidence**."

### "Ceci n'est pas une école" — when "learning" doesn't mean learning

In **"Ceci n'est pas une école"** (Blikstein, Zheng & Zhou, *European Journal of Education* 57(4), 2022, pp. 571–583; DOI: 10.1111/ejed.12528; Paper of the Year Award 2022), the Magritte reference is precise: just as Magritte's pipe was a representation, not a pipe, AIEd products claiming to provide "learning" or "intelligence" are representations that may be fundamentally different from what those terms mean in education. The paper finds that terms like "smart" and "intelligent" in AIEd marketing exploit polysemy — the same word meaning different things in cognitive science and computer science — to claim educational value by linguistic sleight of hand.

### The keychain syndrome and the difference between doing and learning

Blikstein's concept of the "keychain syndrome" (from "Digital Fabrication and 'Making' in Education," in *FabLabs: Of Machines, Makers and Inventors*, Transcript Publishers, 2013) captures how maker education can be "captured" by simplicity. Students introduced to laser cutters loved making keychains — aesthetically attractive, socially admired — and resisted moving to more complex activities like robotics. The syndrome reveals "a disproportionate payoff in staying at a 'local minimum' where the projects are very simple but at the same time very admired by external observers." Students had "discovered exactly what manufacturing is about — mass-producing with little effort — and were using the lab as a fabrication facility, rather than a place for invention."

This illustrates the broader point developed in Valente & Blikstein (*Constructivist Foundations* 14(3), 2019): "The construction of a product is fundamental. However, students' having produced something **is not enough to ensure that they have constructed knowledge.**" The same applies to AI tutoring: completing exercises is not the same as learning.

### Constructionism vs. adaptive tutoring — fundamentally different theories of learning

The deepest divide in Blikstein's work is between Papert's constructionism (students build knowledge by creating artifacts, influenced by Piaget and sharing Freire's liberatory goals) and adaptive tutoring (delivering pre-determined content in a personalized sequence). In "Travels in Troy with Freire" (*Social Justice Education for Teachers*, Sense Publishers, 2008), Blikstein writes: "The most revolutionary aspect of the computer, at least from a Constructionist perspective, is not to use it as an information machine, but as a construction machine." Using a computer as an information delivery device — which is what adaptive tutoring does — is precisely the opposite of what Papert advocated. Blikstein quotes Larry Berger, CEO of Amplify, who confessed at an ASU conference: "I was a great believer in 'personalized learning'... Here's the problem: The learning map doesn't exist, the measurement is impossible, and we have, collectively, built only 5% of the library."

### Direct statements on AI

Blikstein at a Stanford MediaX talk summarized five key points: (1) "When we talk about machine learning or teaching machines, we're also altering our metaphor of human learning"; (2) "The use of teaching machines has an **80-year history, but the results are not encouraging**"; (3) "Educational researchers mostly know why these attempts fail, but communication between educators, cognitive scientists, and technologists is faulty"; (4) Some AI applications show promise but "their business models are still ill-defined"; (5) "The biggest impact of AI in education might come from applications that do not even exist today, and will likely not come from the replacement of teachers or legacy education infrastructure."

On equity, in *Nature* (2023): "If you settle for something cheap, it can take over your whole system. Then five years later, it's the new normal." His core fear: wealthier districts will apply AI "with an emphasis on human interaction and project-based learning, while poorer schools might move increasingly towards automation to save money."

