## SECTION 4: The Khan/Levitt claims under a methodological microscope

This section requires the highest rigor. The claims around Khan Academy and Steve Levitt's evaluation are presented as evidence of AI tutoring's transformative potential. The evidence does not support that conclusion.

### The Khan World School evaluation — co-designer, not evaluator

Khan World School (KWS) at ASU Prep launched in August 2022 with **47 ninth-grade students** (ASU Prep's own press materials; Sal Khan rounded to "50" on Levitt's podcast). Out-of-state tuition: **$10,000/year**. Students self-selected by submitting transcripts, standardized test scores, and recommendation letters. The school describes its target as "self-driven and curious students" and "accelerated students who are motivated by curiosity."

The claimed results — **4.6x typical growth in math, 3.4x in reading, 5.3x in language arts** — were measured using ExactPath (Edmentum), a diagnostic assessment, compared to ExactPath national norms for "typical growth."

**⚠️ This was not a randomized controlled trial. It was not peer-reviewed. It was not even published as a research paper.** The results were announced via (1) a BusinessWire press release (March 9, 2023), (2) Sal Khan's LinkedIn post, and (3) Steve Levitt's podcast "People I (Mostly) Admire."

**⚠️ Levitt is not an independent evaluator.** He co-designed the school. His team at the University of Chicago Center for RISC designed the seminar curriculum. He donated money for student scholarships. He promoted the school on his podcast and encouraged enrollment. The conflict of interest is fundamental.

The methodological problems are severe:

- **N ≈ 47**: Far too small for statistical reliability
- **No control group**: "Typical growth" references ExactPath national norms, not a matched comparison group
- **Extreme selection bias**: Families paying $10,000/year for an experimental online school with application requirements are not representative
- **No peer review**: No published statistical analysis, no external replication
- **Regression to the mean**: Students who test low initially will tend to show larger gains regardless of intervention

Levitt's own words reveal the emotional rather than analytical nature of his assessment: "The test score results for Khan World School — they are so good that when the Khan World School people sent me the test results, I actually thought that they must have made some kind of mistake."

### The Newark study — Khan's own team, modest effects

Khan Academy's 2025 Newark study (Yamkovenko & Grimaldi, Khan Academy technical report) examined ~8,000 students in 13 schools over three years. It used teacher, student, and year fixed effects — a quasi-experimental design, not an RCT. The finding: every **10 new skills mastered = ~1 additional point on NJSLA**; students mastering 60 additional skills gained **6–8 points on a 650–850 scale**.

Context matters. The state average year-to-year gain is ~2 points; the district average ~4 points. So 6 additional points is "close to triple the state average." But on a 200-point scale, a **6–8 point gain represents a 3–4% change** in the total range. The practical significance is debatable. Moreover, **both authors are Khan Academy employees** — this is not independent evaluation. The study cannot distinguish whether students who used Khan Academy more were simply more motivated to begin with (a classic confound in usage-based studies).

### The PNAS study (2026) — the most rigorous evidence, and what it shows

The strongest study to date is Eames, Brunskill, Yamkovenko, Weatherholtz & Oreopoulos, "Computer-assisted learning in the real world," *PNAS* 123(1), 2026. Examining ~200,000 students, it found increasing weekly Khan Academy usage by 30 minutes or mastering 60 skills/year produced gains of **0.09–0.18 standard deviations** on MAP Growth assessments. Two of five authors are Khan Academy employees. Average actual usage was only **10–15 minutes per week** — well below recommended thresholds. A correction was issued in March 2026.

The effect sizes of **0.09–0.18 SD** should be placed in context: high-quality human tutoring produces **0.29–0.37 SD** (Nickow et al., 2024). Khan Academy's AI tutoring, at recommended dosage, produces roughly **one-quarter to one-half the effect of a human tutor**.

### Bloom's two-sigma — the foundation is sand

Sal Khan's entire framing of AI tutoring rests on Benjamin Bloom's 1984 "two-sigma problem" — the claim that one-on-one tutoring produces two standard deviations of improvement, moving a student from the 50th to the 98th percentile. Khan explicitly invoked this in a **May 2023 TED talk titled "The Two Sigma Solution"** to promote Khanmigo's launch, and in *Brave New Words* (2024) he declares: "With Khanmigo, I think we have an artificial intelligence that is hard to distinguish from a strong human tutor."

Paul von Hippel (UT Austin) demolished the two-sigma claim in **"Two-Sigma Tutoring: Separating Science Fiction from Science Fact," *Education Next* 24(2), Spring 2024, pp. 22–31**. His findings:

- **Bloom relied on just two unpublished dissertations** by his own PhD students (Joanne Anania and Arthur J. Burke). Neither ever published the research. No further tutoring studies followed.
- The intervention combined tutoring with extra testing, feedback, and retesting. Von Hippel estimates **testing and feedback alone accounted for ~1.1 of the 2.0 sigmas**, leaving ~0.9 attributable to tutoring.
- Tutoring **replaced** classroom instruction entirely (it didn't supplement it), and students were tested on **narrow topics they started out knowing nothing about** (probability, cartography).
- **Cohen, Kulik & Kulik's 1982 meta-analysis** (*American Educational Research Journal* 19(2), pp. 237–248) found average tutoring effects of **0.33 SD** across 65 studies. Only one study reported a two-sigma effect — a 1972 dissertation with 32 students.
- **Nickow, Oreopoulos & Quan (2024)**, published in *American Educational Research Journal* 61, pp. 74–107, meta-analyzed **96 randomized studies** and found average effects of **0.288 SD. None of the 96 studies produced a two-sigma effect.**
- Matthew Kraft (Brown, 2020) has shown that most educational interventions produce effects of **0.1 SD or less**, and that Bloom "helped to anchor education researchers' expectations for unrealistically large effect sizes."

Von Hippel specifically called out Khan: "It seems rash, though, to promise two-sigma effects from AI when human tutoring has rarely produced such large effects, and **no evidence on the effects of chatbot tutoring has yet been published.**"

### The SRI study — the most independent evaluation of Khan Academy

The SRI International evaluation (Murphy et al., 2014), funded by the Gates Foundation, studied 9 sites, 20 schools, ~2,000 students over two years. Key limitations: "No single implementation model was used across all the sites, and Khan Academy was not used as the sole, or even primary source of math instruction at most sites, making it difficult to isolate its effects." Positive associations appeared at only 2 of 9 sites. Critically, **74% of teachers rated Khan Academy "very effective" for students ahead of grade level, but only 25% gave the same rating for struggling students.** One teacher observed: "The same students who struggled in her classroom before the introduction of Khan Academy also struggled to make progress in Khan Academy." Eleven of 14 schools decreased Khan Academy usage significantly in year two.

**⚠️ Summary of evidence quality**: No peer-reviewed RCT of Khanmigo or any Khan Academy AI tutoring tool exists. The most rigorous observational study (PNAS 2026) shows effect sizes of 0.09–0.18 SD — modest, and roughly one-quarter to one-half the effect of human tutoring. The Bloom two-sigma claim that Khan uses as his foundation has been comprehensively debunked. The KWS/Levitt results are methodologically indefensible as evidence of anything beyond selection effects.

