## Conclusion: What the fever pattern reveals

The century-long cycle of edtech hype is not a story of failed technologies. Film, radio, television, computers, the internet, and AI all possess genuine capabilities. The cycle persists because each wave offers a technological solution to a fundamentally relational problem. Education is labor-intensive, context-dependent, and built on human attachment. Every generation of technologists rediscovers this — usually after billions have been spent.

Three findings from this investigation deserve emphasis because they are novel or underappreciated. **First**, the evidentiary foundation of the current AI-tutoring wave is remarkably thin: Khan's central claim rests on Bloom's two-sigma, which von Hippel has shown was based on two unpublished dissertations and has never been replicated in 96 subsequent RCTs. The best available evidence (PNAS 2026) shows AI tutoring effects of 0.09–0.18 SD — meaningful but a fraction of what human tutoring achieves and far from transformative. **Second**, Blikstein's "Educational Soylent" framing identifies the most likely harm: not that AI tutoring will fail universally, but that it will succeed just enough to justify replacing human instruction in the schools that can least afford to lose it, creating a new axis of educational stratification. **Third**, the NICHD "trading up/down" framework offers a genuine resolution: AI helps when it provides what a child's environment lacks and harms when it displaces what was already there. This is not a compromise but an empirically grounded principle that can guide implementation.

The author's book, in connecting the bedtime story to AI tutoring through the concept of the relational container, has the intellectual architecture right. The bedtime story is the paradigmatic case of a relational technology — its effectiveness depends on attachment, not content. AI tutoring is the paradigmatic case of a content technology — its effectiveness depends on content delivery, not relationship. The question is whether AI can be designed to serve the relational container rather than replace it. The evidence says it can — but only under conditions (human oversight, pedagogical guardrails, augmentation rather than replacement) that are more expensive, more complex, and less scalable than the current hype cycle promises.
